    {
        "content": "<p>According to Wikipedia, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/sequential_space\">docs#sequential_space</a> is called a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fr%C3%A9chet%E2%80%93Urysohn_space\">Fr√©chet‚ÄìUrysohn space</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/is_seq_closed_iff_is_closed\">docs#is_seq_closed_iff_is_closed</a> is the definition of a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequential_space\">sequential space</a>. Is it correct? If yes, should we fix the definition?</p>",
        "id": 281436105,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1651842671
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>a sequential space is a topological space whose topology can be completely characterized by its convergent/divergent sequences.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Fr√©chet‚ÄìUrysohn spaces are exactly those spaces for which knowledge of which sequences converge to which limits (and which sequences do not) suffices to completely determine the space's topology.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmm</p>",
        "id": 281436715,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1651842987
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, these are two formalizations of the same idea.</p>",
        "id": 281436957,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1651843109
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's fair. The informal descriptions make it sound like the concepts are equivalent :-)</p>",
        "id": 281437139,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1651843201
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But if these are the commonly accepted names, we should follow them.</p>",
        "id": 281437275,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1651843246
    },
    {
