    {
        "content": "<p>I guess, exactly Fr√©chet-Urysohn. Suppose that this is true for any <code>f : Œ± ‚Üí bool</code> (with the discrete topology on <code>bool</code>). Take a set <code>s : set Œ±</code> and a point <code>a ‚àà closure s</code>. Then <code>f : Œª x, if x ‚àà s then tt else ff</code> does not tend to <code>ff</code> as <code>x ‚Üí a</code>. Thus there exists <code>u : nat ‚Üí Œ±</code> that converges to <code>a</code> such that <code>f ‚àò u</code> does not converge to <code>ff</code>. This means that infinitely many <code>u k</code> belong to <code>s</code>, so we can take this subsequence.</p>",
        "id": 281447029,
